sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="X." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. aenescens" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aenescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. aenescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be separated from those of other species in the genus by their entirely green elytra, presence of three black spots on the pronotum, and elytra with fine and dense punctures. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lee &amp; Bezděk" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xanthogaleruca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xanthogaleruca yuae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yuae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xanthogaleruca yuae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="X." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. aenescens" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aenescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. aenescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a narrower aedeagus, 5.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Diagnostic characters of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E gonocoxae F abdominal ventrite VIII G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I tarsi of front leg, male J tarsi of front leg, female K apex of tibia of middle leg, male L spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545533" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3C, D</figureCitation>
) (broader aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Diagnostic characters of Xanthogaleruca aenescens (Fairmaire) A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E gonocoxae F abdominal ventrite VIII G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I apex of tibia of middle leg, male J tarsi of front leg, male K tarsi of front leg, female L spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545532" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2C, D</figureCitation>
), 5.1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide in 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="X." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. aenescens" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aenescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. aenescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), teeth from near apex to middle of primary endophallic sclerite (lacking teeth from near apex to middle of primary endophallic sclerite in 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="X." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. aenescens" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aenescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. aenescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), apex of tarsomere I of front legs broader in males than females (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Diagnostic characters of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E gonocoxae F abdominal ventrite VIII G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I tarsi of front leg, male J tarsi of front leg, female K apex of tibia of middle leg, male L spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545533" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3I, J</figureCitation>
) (apex of tarsomere I of front legs uniform in both sexes of 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="X." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. aenescens" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aenescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. aenescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Diagnostic characters of Xanthogaleruca aenescens (Fairmaire) A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E gonocoxae F abdominal ventrite VIII G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I apex of tibia of middle leg, male J tarsi of front leg, male K tarsi of front leg, female L spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545532" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">2J, K</figureCitation>
)), and long apical spur on mesotibia (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Diagnostic characters of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E gonocoxae F abdominal ventrite VIII G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I tarsi of front leg, male J tarsi of front leg, female K apex of tibia of middle leg, male L spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545533" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3K</figureCitation>
) (short apical spur on mesotibia in 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="X." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="X. aenescens" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="aenescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. aenescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Diagnostic characters of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E gonocoxae F abdominal ventrite VIII G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I tarsi of front leg, male J tarsi of front leg, female K apex of tibia of middle leg, male L spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545533" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3I</figureCitation>
)). This new species was misidentified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire" baseAuthorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xanthogaleruca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xanthogaleruca aenescens" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aenescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xanthogaleruca aenescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kimoto, S" journalOrPublisher="Esakia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 68" publicationUrl="https://catalog.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_detail_md/?lang=0&amp;amode=MD100000&amp;bibid=2358" refId="B25" refString="Kimoto, S, 1969. Notes on the Chrysomelidae from Taiwan, II. Esakia 7: 1 - 68, https://catalog.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_detail_md/?lang=0&amp;amode=MD100000&amp;bibid=2358" title="Notes on the Chrysomelidae from Taiwan, II." url="https://catalog.lib.kyushu-u.ac.jp/opac_detail_md/?lang=0&amp;amode=MD100000&amp;bibid=2358" volume="7" year="1969">Kimoto (1969</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kimoto, S" journalOrPublisher="Kurume University Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="53 - 62" refId="B31" refString="Kimoto, S, 1986. The Chrysomelidae (Insecta: Coleoptera) collected by the Nagoya University Scientific Expedition to Taiwan in 1984. Kurume University Journal 35: 53 - 62" title="The Chrysomelidae (Insecta: Coleoptera) collected by the Nagoya University Scientific Expedition to Taiwan in 1984." volume="35" year="1986">1986</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="host">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Host plants.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Larvae and adults feed on leaves of 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="Zelkova" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Zelkova serrata" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="serrata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Zelkova serrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Thunb.) Makino (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spach" authorityYear="1841" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Ulmaceae" genus="Zelkova" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Urticales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Ulmaceae</taxonomicName>
) (present study).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lee &amp; Bezděk" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Xanthogaleruca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xanthogaleruca yuae" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yuae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xanthogaleruca yuae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. populations are presumed to be univoltine. The following life cycle information is based on our (TCRT) observations made by Mr Mei-Hua Tsou (Lee and Cheng 2010). Females began to deposit an average of 10-20 eggs in two rows of a single egg mass on the undersides of leaves (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Field photographs of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. on host plant A egg masses B early instar larva C mature larvae D single mature larva E pupa and prepupa F adult." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545534" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4A</figureCitation>
) during 22 April 2009. Larvae hatched in 7-8 days. Larvae fed on one side of leaves and left only one layer of tissue at the surface (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Field photographs of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. on host plant A egg masses B early instar larva C mature larvae D single mature larva E pupa and prepupa F adult." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545534" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4B, C</figureCitation>
). The larval duration was 15-21 days. mature larvae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Field photographs of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. on host plant A egg masses B early instar larva C mature larvae D single mature larva E pupa and prepupa F adult." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545534" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4D</figureCitation>
) expelled an adhesive from the anus, then pupated on the undersides of leaves. Duration of the pupal stage was 8-13 days (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Field photographs of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. on host plant A egg masses B early instar larva C mature larvae D single mature larva E pupa and prepupa F adult." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545534" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4E</figureCitation>
). adults were active during spring (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Field photographs of Xanthogaleruca yuae sp. nov. on host plant A egg masses B early instar larva C mature larvae D single mature larva E pupa and prepupa F adult." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545534" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">4F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
